# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-storage-gateway
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM may also be used where more robust storage is available for long-term archiving, but this is slow to access.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] This may be as simple as an off-site backup for recovery from disaster.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM is a long-established concept, dating back to the beginnings of commercial data processing.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The techniques used though have changed significantly as new technology becomes available, for both storage and for long-distance communication of large data sets.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The scale of measures such as 'size' and 'access time' have changed dramatically.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Despite this, many of the underlying concepts keep returning to favour years later, although at much larger or faster scales.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] In a typical HSM scenario, data which is frequently used are stored on warm storage device, such as solid-state disk (SSD).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Data that is infrequently accessed is, after some time *migrated* to a slower, high capacity cold storage tier.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] If a user does access data which is on the cold storage tier, it is automatically moved back to warm storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The advantage is that the total amount of stored data can be much larger than the capacity of the warm storage device, but since only rarely used files are on cold storage, most users will usually not notice any slowdown.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] In practice, HSM is typically performed by dedicated software, such as IBM Tivoli Storage Manager, or Oracle's SAM-QFS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The deletion of files from a higher level of the hierarchy (e.g. magnetic disk) after they have been moved to a lower level (e.g. optical media) is sometimes called **file grooming**.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Hierarchical Storage Manager (HSM, then DFHSM and finally DFSMShsm) was first implemented by IBM on March 31, 1978 for MVS to reduce the cost of data storage, and to simplify the retrieval of data from slower media.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The user would not need to know where the data was stored and how to get it back; the computer would retrieve the data automatically.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The only difference to the user was the speed at which data was returned.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM could originally migrate datasets only to disk volumes and virtual volumes on a IBM 3850 Mass Storage Facility, but a later release supported magnetic tape volumes for migration level 2 (ML2).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Later, IBM ported HSM to its AIX operating system, and then to other Unix-like operating systems such as Solaris, HP-UX and Linux.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] CSIRO Australia's Division of Computing Research implemented an HSM in its DAD (Drums and Display) operating system with its Document Region in the 1960s, with copies of documents being written to 7-track tape and automatic retrieval upon access to the documents.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM was also implemented on the DEC VAX/VMS systems and the Alpha/VMS systems.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The first implementation date should be readily determined from the VMS System Implementation Manuals or the VMS Product Description Brochures.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM is often used for deep archival storage of data to be held long term at low cost.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Automated tape robots can silo large quantities of data efficiently with low power consumption.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Some HSM software products allow the user to place portions of data files on high-speed disk cache and the rest on tape.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] This is used in applications that stream video over the internet—the initial portion of a video is delivered immediately from disk while a robot finds, mounts and streams the rest of the file to the end user.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Such a system greatly reduces disk cost for large content provision systems.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] HSM software is today used also for tiering between hard disk drives and flash memory, with flash memory being over 30 times faster than magnetic disks, but disks being considerably cheaper.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The key factor behind HSM is a data migration policy that controls the file transfers in the system.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] More precisely, the policy decides which tier a file should be stored in, so that the entire storage system can be well-organized and have a shortest response time to requests.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] There are several algorithms realizing this process, such as least recently used replacement (LRU), Size-Temperature Replacement(STP), Heuristic Threshold(STEP) etc.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] In research of recent years, there are also some intelligent policies coming up by using machine learning technologies.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] While tiering solutions and caching may look the same on the surface, the fundamental differences lie in the way the faster storage is utilized and the algorithms used to detect and accelerate frequently accessed data.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Caching operates by making a copy of frequently accessed blocks of data, and storing the copy in the faster storage device and use this copy instead of the original data source on the slower, high capacity backend storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Every time a storage read occurs, the caching software look to see if a copy of this data already exists on the cache and uses that copy, if available.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Otherwise, the data is read from the slower, high capacity storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Tiering on the other hand operates very differently.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Rather than making a *copy* of frequently accessed data into fast storage, tiering *moves* data across tiers, for example, by relocating cold data to low cost, high capacity nearline storage devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] The basic idea is, mission-critical and highly accesses or "hot" data is stored in expensive medium such as SSD to take advantage of high I/O performance, while nearline or rarely accessed or "cold" data is stored in nearline storage medium such as HDD and tapes which are inexpensive.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/hierarchical-storage-management] Thus, the "data temperature" or activity levels determines the primary storage hierarchy.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] Nearline storage dates back to the IBM 3850 Mass Storage System (MSS) tape library, which was announced in 1974.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] For example, always-on spinning hard disk drives are online storage, while spinning drives that spin down automatically, such as in Massive Arrays of Idle Disks (MAID), are nearline storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] Removable media such as tape cartridges that can be automatically loaded, as in tape libraries, are nearline storage, while tape cartridges that must be manually loaded are offline storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] This process is not instant, but it only requires a few seconds.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] Nearline tape and optical storage has the advantage of relatively longer lifespans compared to spinning hard drives, simply due to the storage media being idle and usually stored in protected dust-free enclosures when not in use.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] In a robotic tape loading system, the tape drive used for accessing data experiences the most wear and may need occasional replacement, but the tapes themselves can last for years to decades.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] If there are sealable access doors between the access mechanism and the media, it is possible for the idle media storage enclosure to survive fire, floods, lightning strikes, and other disasters.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] MAID (massive array of idle drives) systems archive data in an array of hard disk drives, with most drives in a MAID usually stopped.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] The MAID system spins up each drive on demand when necessary to read (or in some cases to write) data on that drive.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] For a given amount of storage capacity, MAID systems have higher densities and lower power and cooling requirements than "hot" storage systems that keep all the disks spinning at full speed at all times.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] Some hard drive and storage systems vendors and suppliers use the term in reference to low-rotational speed hard drives that are built to be more reliable than generic desktop and laptop computer hard drives.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] They are intended to be operational continuously for 24 hours a day, seven days a week, possibly for several years.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] Nearline hard drives may be used in personal or small business network-attached storage (NAS) systems, or as non-critical moderate-performance data storage on servers, where greater durability is required for the drive to operate continuously.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] By comparison, standard hard drives are assumed to only be in operation for a few hours each day, and are not spinning when the computer is either turned off or in sleep mode.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] Standard hard drives may also use data caching methods that can improve single-drive performance, but would interfere with the operation of multi-drive RAID storage systems, potentially causing data loss or corruption.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/nearline-storage] Specifically the term *nearline hard drive* is being used to refer to high-capacity Serial ATA drives that work with Serial Attached SCSI storage devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] A NAS device is optimised for serving files either by its hardware, software, or configuration.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] It is often manufactured as a computer appliance – a purpose-built specialized computer.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS systems are networked appliances that contain one or more storage drives, often arranged into logical, redundant storage containers or RAID.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Network-attached storage typically provide access to files using network file sharing protocols such as NFS, SMB, or AFP.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Accompanying a NAS are purpose-built hard disk drives, which are functionally similar to non-NAS drives but may have different firmware, vibration tolerance, or power dissipation to make them more suitable for use in RAID arrays, a technology often used in NAS implementations.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] For example, some NAS versions of drives support a command extension to allow extended error recovery to be disabled.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] In a non-RAID application, it may be important for a disk drive to go to great lengths to successfully read a problematic storage block, even if it takes several seconds.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] In an appropriately configured RAID array, a single bad block on a single drive can be recovered completely via the redundancy encoded across the RAID set.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] A NAS unit is a computer connected to a network that provides only file-based data storage services to other devices on the network.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Although it may technically be possible to run other software on a NAS unit, it is usually not designed to be a general-purpose server.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] For example, NAS units usually do not have a keyboard or display, and are controlled and configured over the network, often using a browser.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] A full-featured operating system is not needed on a NAS device, so often a stripped-down operating system is used.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS systems contain one or more hard disk drives, often arranged into logical, redundant storage containers or RAID.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS uses file-based protocols such as NFS (popular on UNIX systems), SMB (Server Message Block) (used with Microsoft Windows systems), AFP (used with Apple Macintosh computers), or NCP (used with OES and Novell NetWare).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS units rarely limit clients to a single protocol.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The key difference between direct-attached storage (DAS) and NAS is that DAS is simply an extension to an existing server and is not necessarily networked.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] As the name suggests, DAS typically is connected via a USB or Thunderbolt enabled cable.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS is designed as an easy and self-contained solution for sharing files over the network.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Both DAS and NAS can potentially increase availability of data by using RAID or clustering.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Both NAS and DAS can have various amount of cache memory, which greatly affects performance.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] When comparing use of NAS with use of local (non-networked) DAS, the performance of NAS depends mainly on the speed of and congestion on the network.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Most NAS solutions will include the option to install a wide array of software applications to allow better configuration of the system or to include other capabilities outside of storage (like video surveillance, virtualization, media, etc).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] DAS typically is focused solely on data storage but capabilities can be available based on specific vendor options.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS provides both storage and a file system.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] This is often contrasted with SAN (storage area network), which provides only block-based storage and leaves file system concerns on the "client" side.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] SAN protocols include Fibre Channel, iSCSI, ATA over Ethernet (AoE) and HyperSCSI.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Despite their differences, SAN and NAS are not mutually exclusive and may be combined as a SAN-NAS hybrid, offering both file-level protocols (NAS) and block-level protocols (SAN) from the same system.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] A shared disk file system can also be run on top of a SAN to provide filesystem services.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] In the early 1980s, the "Newcastle Connection" by Brian Randell and his colleagues at Newcastle University demonstrated and developed remote file access across a set of UNIX machines.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Novell's NetWare server operating system and NCP protocol was released in 1983.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Following the Newcastle Connection, Sun Microsystems' 1984 release of NFS allowed network servers to share their storage space with networked clients.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] 3Com and Microsoft would develop the LAN Manager software and protocol to further this new market.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] 3Com's 3Server and 3+Share software was the first purpose-built server (including proprietary hardware, software, and multiple disks) for open systems servers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Inspired by the success of file servers from Novell, IBM, and Sun, several firms developed dedicated file servers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] While 3Com was among the first firms to build a dedicated NAS for desktop operating systems, Auspex Systems was one of the first to develop a dedicated NFS server for use in the UNIX market.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] A group of Auspex engineers split away in the early 1990s to create the integrated NetApp FAS, which supported both the Windows SMB and the UNIX NFS protocols and had superior scalability and ease of deployment.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] This started the market for proprietary NAS devices now led by NetApp and EMC Celerra.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] In 2009, NAS vendors (notably CTERA networks and Netgear) began to introduce online backup solutions integrated in their NAS appliances, for online disaster recovery.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] By 2021, three major types of NAS solutions are offered (all with hybrid cloud models where data can be stored both on-premise on the NAS and off site on a separate NAS or through a public cloud service provider).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The first type of NAS is focused on consumer needs with lower-cost options that typically support 1–5 hot plug hard drives.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The second is focused on small-to-medium-sized businesses – these NAS solutions range from 2–24+ hard drives and are typically offered in tower or rackmount form factors.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Pricing can vary greatly depending on the processor, components, and overall features supported.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The last type is geared toward enterprises or large businesses and are offered with more advanced software capabilities.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS solutions are typically sold without hard drives installed to allow the buyer (or IT departments) to select the hard drive cost, size, and quality.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Embedded-system-based NAS – using an ARM- or MIPS-based processor architecture and a real-time operating system (RTOS) or an embedded operating system to run a NAS server.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The power consumption of this NAS type is fair, and functions in the NAS can fit most end-user requirements.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Marvell, Oxford, and Storlink make chipsets for this type of NAS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Max FTP throughput varies from 20 MB/s to 120 MB/s.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] ASIC-based NAS – provisioning NAS through the use of a single ASIC chip, using hardware to implement TCP/IP and file system.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] There is no OS in the chip, as all the performance-related operations are done by hardware acceleration circuits.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The power consumption of this type of NAS is low, as functions are limited to only support SMB and FTP.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] LayerWalker is the only chipset manufacturer for this type of NAS.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS is useful for more than just general centralized storage provided to client computers in environments with large amounts of data.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] NAS can enable simpler and lower cost systems such as load-balancing and fault-tolerant email and web server systems by providing storage services.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] In the consumer market, NAS devices have evolved into "private cloud" solutions.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] They allow users to store multimedia data and back up files from various devices (such as smartphones and PCs) while retaining full data ownership.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Unlike public cloud services, these private cloud setups typically do not require monthly subscription fees for storage capacity.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Such consumer market appliances are now commonly available.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Unlike their rackmounted counterparts, they are generally packaged in smaller form factors.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The price of NAS appliances has fallen sharply in recent years, offering flexible network-based storage to the home consumer market for little more than the cost of a regular USB or FireWire external hard disk.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Many of these home consumer devices are built around ARM, x86 or MIPS processors running an embedded Linux operating system.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] A **purpose-built backup appliance** (PBBA) is a kind of NAS intended for storing backup data.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] PBBAs typically include data deduplication, compression, RAID 6 or other redundant hardware components, and automated maintenance.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] A PBBA may also be called a **backup and disaster recovery appliance** or simply a **backup appliance**.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Open-source NAS-oriented distributions of Linux and FreeBSD are available.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] These are designed to be easy to set up on commodity PC hardware, and are typically configured using a web browser.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] They can run from a virtual machine, Live CD, bootable USB flash drive (Live USB), or from one of the mounted hard drives.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] They run Samba (an SMB daemon), NFS daemon, and FTP daemons which are freely available for those operating systems.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] If the client can be granted access to the file requested, the client receives the network location of NASD disks and their capability.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] If the client is accessing the disk for the first time, it receives a time-limited key for the establishment of secure communication to the disk.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The file manager informs the corresponding disk using an independent channel.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] From now on, the client directly accesses the NASD disks by giving the capability it received and further data transfers go through the network, bypassing the file manager.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] A **clustered NAS** is a NAS that is using a distributed file system running simultaneously on multiple servers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] The key difference between a clustered and traditional NAS is the ability to distribute (e.g. stripe) data and metadata across the cluster nodes or storage devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/network-attached-storage] Clustered NAS, like a traditional one, still provides unified access to the files from any of the cluster nodes, unrelated to the actual location of the data.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] A "storage system" is also known as a storage array, disk array, or *filer*.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Storage systems typically use special hardware and software along with disk drives in order to provide very fast and reliable storage for computing and data processing.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Storage systems are complex, and may be thought of as a special purpose computer designed to provide storage capacity along with advanced data protection features.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Disk drives are only one element within a storage system, along with hardware and special purpose embedded software within the system.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Storage systems can provide either block accessed storage, or file accessed storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Block access is typically delivered over Fibre Channel, iSCSI, SAS, FICON or other protocols.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] File access is often provided using NFS or SMB protocols.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Virtualization of storage helps achieve location independence by abstracting the physical location of the data.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The virtualization system presents to the user a logical space for data storage and handles the process of mapping it to the actual physical location.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] It is possible to have multiple layers of virtualization or mapping.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] It is then possible that the output of one layer of virtualization can then be used as the input for a higher layer of virtualization.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Virtualization maps space between back-end resources, to front-end resources.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In this instance, "back-end" refers to a logical unit number (LUN) that is not presented to a computer, or host system for direct use.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] A "front-end" LUN or volume is presented to a host or computer system for use.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The actual form of the mapping will depend on the chosen implementation.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Some implementations may limit the granularity of the mapping which may limit the capabilities of the device.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Typical granularities range from a single physical disk down to some small subset (multiples of megabytes or gigabytes) of the physical disk.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In a block-based storage environment, a single block of information is addressed using a LUN identifier and an offset within that LUN – known as a logical block addressing (LBA).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The virtualization software or device is responsible for maintaining a consistent view of all the mapping information for the virtualized storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This mapping information is often called metadata and is stored as a mapping table.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The address space may be limited by the capacity needed to maintain the mapping table.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The level of granularity, and the total addressable space both directly impact the size of the meta-data, and hence the mapping table.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] For this reason, it is common to have trade-offs, between the amount of addressable capacity and the granularity or access granularity.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] One common method to address these limits is to use multiple levels of virtualization.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In several storage systems deployed today, it is common to utilize three layers of virtualization.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Some implementations do not use a mapping table, and instead calculate locations using an algorithm.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] These implementations utilize dynamic methods to calculate the location on access, rather than storing the information in a mapping table.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The virtualization software or device uses the metadata to re-direct I/O requests.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] It will receive an incoming I/O request containing information about the location of the data in terms of the logical disk (vdisk) and translates this into a new I/O request to the physical disk location.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Most implementations allow for heterogeneous management of multi-vendor storage devices within the scope of a given implementation's support matrix.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This means that the following capabilities are not limited to a single vendor's device (as with similar capabilities provided by specific storage controllers) and are in fact possible across different vendors' devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Data replication techniques are not limited to virtualization appliances and as such are not described here in detail.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] However most implementations will provide some or all of these replication services.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] When storage is virtualized, replication services must be implemented above the software or device that is performing the virtualization.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This is true because it is only above the virtualization layer that a true and consistent image of the logical disk (vdisk) can be copied.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This limits the services that some implementations can implement – or makes them seriously difficult to implement.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] If the virtualization is implemented in the network or higher, this renders any replication services provided by the underlying storage controllers useless.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The physical storage resources are aggregated into storage pools, from which the logical storage is created.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] More storage systems, which may be heterogeneous in nature, can be added as and when needed, and the virtual storage space will scale up by the same amount.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This process is fully transparent to the applications using the storage infrastructure.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The software or device providing storage virtualization becomes a common disk manager in the virtualized environment.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Logical disks (vdisks) are created by the virtualization software or device and are mapped (made visible) to the required host or server, thus providing a common place or way for managing all volumes in the environment.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] One of the major benefits of abstracting the host or server from the actual storage is the ability to **migrate** data while maintaining concurrent I/O access.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The host only knows about the logical disk (the mapped LUN) and so any changes to the meta-data mapping is transparent to the host.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This means the actual data can be moved or replicated to another physical location without affecting the operation of any clieaa5c7597941c0c265ff85b 5b2644754c5cbfb8366f89 7ce5bc82f28656e82136nt.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] When the data has been copied or moved, the meta-data can simply be updated to point to the new location, therefore freeing up the physical storage at the old location.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The process of moving the physical location is known as **data migration**.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Most implementations allow for this to be done in a non-disruptive manner, that is concurrently while the host continues to perform I/O to the logical disk (or LUN).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The mapping granularity dictates how quickly the meta-data can be updated, how much extra capacity is required during the migration, and how quickly the previous location is marked as free.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The smaller the granularity the faster the update, less space required and quicker the old storage can be freed up.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] There are many day to day tasks a storage administrator has to perform that can be simply and concurrently performed using data migration techniques.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Utilization can be increased by virtue of the pooling, migration, and thin provisioning services.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This allows users to avoid over-buying and over-provisioning storage solutions.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In other words, this kind of utilization through a shared pool of storage can be easily and quickly allocated as it is needed to avoid constraints on storage capacity that often hinder application performance.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] When all available storage capacity is pooled, system administrators no longer have to search for disks that have free space to allocate to a particular host or server.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] A new logical disk can be simply allocated from the available pool, or an existing disk can be expanded.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Pooling also means that all the available storage capacity can potentially be used.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In a traditional environment, an entire disk would be mapped to a host.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This may be larger than is required, thus wasting space.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In a virtual environment, the logical disk (LUN) is assigned the capacity required by the using host.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Storage can be assigned where it is needed at that point in time, reducing the need to *guess* how much a given host will need in the future.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Using Thin Provisioning, the administrator can create a very large thin provisioned logical disk, thus the using system thinks it has a very large disk from day one.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] With storage virtualization, multiple independent storage devices, even if scattered across a network, appear to be a single monolithic storage device and can be managed centrally.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] However, traditional storage controller management is still required.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] That is, the creation and maintenance of RAID arrays, including error and fault management.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Once the abstraction layer is in place, only the virtualizer knows where the data actually resides on the physical medium.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Backing out of a virtual storage environment therefore requires the reconstruction of the logical disks as contiguous disks that can be used in a traditional manner.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Most implementations will provide some form of back-out procedure and with the data migration services it is at least possible, but time consuming.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Interoperability is a key enabler to any virtualization software or device.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] It applies to the actual physical storage controllers and the hosts, their operating systems, multi-pathing software and connectivity hardware.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Interoperability requirements differ based on the implementation chosen.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] For example, virtualization implemented within a storage controller adds no extra overhead to host based interoperability, but will require additional support of other storage controllers if they are to be virtualized by the same software.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Switch based virtualization may not require specific host interoperability — if it uses packet cracking techniques to redirect the I/O.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Network based appliances have the highest level of interoperability requirements as they have to interoperate with all devices, storage and hosts.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Information is one of the most valuable assets in today's business environments.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Once virtualized, the metadata are the glue in the middle.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] If the metadata are lost, so is all the actual data as it would be virtually impossible to reconstruct the logical drives without the mapping information.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Any implementation must ensure its protection with appropriate levels of back-ups and replicas.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] It is important to be able to reconstruct the meta-data in the event of a catastrophic failure.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The metadata management also has implications on performance.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Any virtualization software or device must be able to keep all the copies of the metadata atomic and quickly updateable.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Some implementations restrict the ability to provide certain fast update functions, such as point-in-time copies and caching where super fast updates are required to ensure minimal latency to the actual I/O being performed.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In some implementations the performance of the physical storage can actually be improved, mainly due to caching.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Caching however requires the visibility of the data contained within the I/O request and so is limited to in-band and symmetric virtualization software and devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] However these implementations also directly influence the latency of an I/O request (cache miss), due to the I/O having to flow through the software or device.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Assuming the software or device is efficiently designed this impact should be minimal when compared with the latency associated with physical disk accesses.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Due to the nature of virtualization, the mapping of logical to physical requires some processing power and lookup tables.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Therefore, every implementation will add some small amount of latency.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In addition to response time concerns, throughput has to be considered.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The bandwidth into and out of the meta-data lookup software directly impacts the available system bandwidth.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In asymmetric implementations, where the meta-data lookup occurs before the information is read or written, bandwidth is less of a concern as the meta-data are a tiny fraction of the actual I/O size.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In-band, symmetric flow through designs are directly limited by their processing power and connectivity bandwidths.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Most implementations provide some form of scale-out model, where the inclusion of additional software or device instances provides increased scalability and potentially increased bandwidth.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The performance and scalability characteristics are directly influenced by the chosen implementation.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Host-based virtualization requires additional software running on the host, as a privileged task or process.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] In some cases volume management is built into the operating system, and in other instances it is offered as a separate product.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Volumes (LUN's) presented to the host system are handled by a traditional physical device driver.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] However, a software layer (the volume manager) resides above the disk device driver intercepts the I/O requests, and provides the meta-data lookup and I/O mapping.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Most modern operating systems have some form of logical volume management built-in (in Linux called Logical Volume Manager or LVM; in Solaris and FreeBSD, ZFS's zpool layer; in Windows called Logical Disk Manager or LDM), that performs virtualization tasks.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Note: Host based volume managers were in use long before the term *storage virtualization* had been coined.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Like host-based virtualization, several categories have existed for years and have only recently been classified as virtualization.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Simple data storage devices, like single hard disk drives, do not provide any virtualization.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] But even the simplest disk arrays provide a logical to physical abstraction, as they use RAID schemes to join multiple disks in a single array (and possibly later divide the array it into smaller volumes).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Advanced disk arrays often feature cloning, snapshots and remote replication.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Generally these devices do not provide the benefits of data migration or replication across heterogeneous storage, as each vendor tends to use their own proprietary protocols.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] A new breed of disk array controllers allows the downstream attachment of other storage devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] For the purposes of this article we will only discuss the later style which do actually virtualize other storage devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] A primary storage controller provides the services and allows the direct attachment of other storage controllers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Depending on the implementation these may be from the same or different vendors.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The primary controller will provide the pooling and meta-data management services.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] It may also provide replication and migration services across those controllers which it is .
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Storage virtualization operating on a network based device (typically a standard server or smart switch) and using iSCSI or FC Fibre channel networks to connect as a SAN.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] These types of devices are the most commonly available and implemented form of virtualization.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The virtualization device sits in the SAN and provides the layer of abstraction between the hosts performing the I/O and the storage controllers providing the storage capacity.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] There are two commonly available implementations of network-based storage virtualization, appliance-based and switch-based.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Both models can provide the same services, disk management, metadata lookup, data migration and replication.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Both models also require some processing hardware to provide these services.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Appliance based devices are dedicated hardware devices that provide SAN connectivity of one form or another.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] These sit between the hosts and storage and in the case of in-band (symmetric) appliances can provide all of the benefits and services discussed in this article.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] I/O requests are targeted at the appliance itself, which performs the meta-data mapping before redirecting the I/O by sending its own I/O request to the underlying storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The in-band appliance can also provide caching of data, and most implementations provide some form of clustering of individual appliances to maintain an atomic view of the metadata as well as cache data.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Switch based devices, as the name suggests, reside in the physical switch hardware used to connect the SAN devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] These also sit between the hosts and storage but may use different techniques to provide the metadata mapping, such as packet cracking to snoop on incoming I/O requests and perform the I/O redirection.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] It is much more difficult to ensure atomic updates of metadata in a switched environment and services requiring fast updates of data and metadata may be limited in switched implementations.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] File-based virtualization is a type of storage virtualization that uses files as the basic unit of storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This is in contrast to block-based storage virtualization, which uses blocks as the basic unit.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] It is a way to abstract away the physical details of storage and allow files to be stored on any type of storage device, without the need for specific drivers or other low-level configuration.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] File-based virtualization can be used for storage consolidation, improved storage utilization, virtualization and disaster recovery.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] This can simplify storage administration and reduce the overall number of storage devices that need to be managed.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] System administrators and software developers administer the virtual storage through offline operations using built-in or third-party tools.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The virtual disk is implemented as either split over a collection of flat files, typically each one is 2GB in size, collectively called a *split* flat file, or as a single, large *monolithic* flat file.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The pre-allocated storage scheme is also referred to as a *thick provisioning* scheme.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The virtual disk can again be implemented using split or monolithic files, except that storage is allocated on demand.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] Several Virtual Machine Monitor implementations initialize the storage with zeros before providing it to the virtual machine that is in operation.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] The dynamic growth storage scheme is also referred to as a *thin provisioning* scheme.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] File-based virtualization can also improve storage utilization by allowing files to be stored on devices that are not being used to their full capacity.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] For example, if a file server has a number of hard drives that are only partially filled, file-based virtualization can be used to store files on those drives, thereby increasing the utilization of the storage devices.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/storage-virtualization] File-based virtualization can be used to create a virtual file server (or virtual NAS device), which is a storage system that appears to the user as a single file server but which is actually implemented as a set of files stored on a number of physical file servers.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] In computer architecture, the **memory hierarchy** separates computer storage into a hierarchy based on response time.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Since response time, complexity, and capacity are related, the levels may also be distinguished by their performance and controlling technologies.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Memory hierarchy affects performance in computer architectural design, algorithm predictions, and lower level programming constructs involving locality of reference.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Designing for high performance requires considering the restrictions of the memory hierarchy, i.e. the size and capabilities of each component.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Each of the various components can be viewed as part of a hierarchy of memories (*m*1, *m*2, ..., *mn*) in which each member mi is typically smaller and faster than the next highest member *m**i*+1 of the hierarchy.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] To limit waiting by higher levels, a lower level will respond by filling a buffer and then signaling for activating the transfer.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] This is a general memory hierarchy structuring.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] For example, a paging algorithm may be considered as a level for virtual memory when designing a computer architecture, and one can include a level of nearline storage between online and offline storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] The number of levels in the memory hierarchy and the performance at each level has increased over time.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] The type of memory or storage components also change historically.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Some CPUs include additional levels of cache between L3 and memory.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] For example, the Haswell microarchitecture includes an L4 cache of 128 MB on mobile units.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] The lower levels of the hierarchy – from mass storage downwards – are also known as tiered storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] For example, always-on spinning disks are online, while spinning disks that spin down, such as massive arrays of idle disk (MAID), are nearline.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Removable media such as tape cartridges that can be automatically loaded, as in a tape library, are nearline, while cartridges that must be manually loaded are offline.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Most modern CPUs are so fast that, for most program workloads, the bottleneck is the locality of reference of memory accesses and the efficiency of the caching and memory transfer between different levels of the hierarchy.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] As a result, the CPU spends much of its time idling, waiting for memory I/O to complete.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] This is sometimes called the *space cost*, as a larger memory object is more likely to overflow a small and fast level and require use of a larger, slower level.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] The resulting load on memory use is known as *pressure* (respectively *register pressure*, *cache pressure*, and (main) *memory pressure*).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Modern programming languages mainly assume two levels of memory, main (*working*) memory and mass storage.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] The exception is the relatively low-level assembly language and in the inline assemblers of higher-level languages such as C where "prefetch" instructions can be used to preload the cache.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Many programmers assume one level of memory.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] This works fine until the application hits a performance wall.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] At that point, the programmer needs to change the code's memory access patterns to that it works well with cache resources.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] A classic illustration of the effect of locality and caching is in the form of changing the order of iterating a three-dimensional array.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] *Computer Systems: A Programmer's Perspective* is a classic textbook that deals with this aspect of systems programming.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] Memory tiering is implemented on Linux as an extension to NUMA, where each memory provider has a CPU-less NUMA node with an appropriate "abstract distance" reflecting its performance.
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] The existing scheme for migrating memory between NUMA nodes using "hotness" indicated by page faults is adapted to tiering by Huang Ying (Al Maruf's TPP scheme is not in Linux mainline).
[src:aws-storage-gateway/tiered-storage] It also uses a weighted-interleave allocation policy.
